Classical Brownian Motion
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import animation, rc
from IPython.display import HTML

np.random.seed(140)

Lets begin by defining Brownian Motion.

Definition: Brownian motion, denoted $B_t$ for $t>0$, is a stochastic process such that

  1. $B_0$ = 0
  2. $B_t$ is continous almost surely
  3. The increments of the process are normally distributed. $B_t - B_s \sim N(0, |t-s|)$
  4. If $0 \leq t_1 < t_2 < t_3 < t_4$ then $B_{t_2} - B_{t_1}$ is independent of $B_{t_4} - B_{t_3}$

Suppose we want to simulate Brownian Motion from $0$ to $t_{\text{max}} = 2$ with 500 frames.

t_max = 2
frames = 500

This means we will update our time every $\frac{t_{max}}{\text{frames}}$ seconds for $0 \leq t \leq t_{\text{max}}$

t = np.linspace(0, t_max, frames)

Next we create an array of normally distributed numbers which will represent the increments at each time step. The variance of these numbers is $\frac{\text{frames}}{t_{\text{max}}}$ so that the variance of an increment over a second will be one.

interval_displacement = np.random.normal(scale = np.sqrt(frames/t_max), size=len(t))

The motion of our process is simply the cumulative sum of this array. After all, the position of a sequence is the sequence of partial sums of displacement.

BM = np.cumsum(interval_displacement)

Next we want to set up the figure of our plot. Obviously we want our horizontal axis to go from $0$ to $t_{max}$. We can make the vertical axis go from the minimum value to the maximum value our process acheived so that we are guaranteed to be able to visualize the entire path. We should also make sure to title our axes and title our plot

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.set_xlim((0, t_max))
vertical_height = max(abs(max((BM))), abs(min(BM)))
ax.set_ylim(min(BM),max(BM))
plt.title("Path of Brownian Motion")
plt.xlabel("t")
plt.ylabel("$B_t$")
plt.close();

Next we can define a function that traces our process throughout time and creates an animation.

line, = ax.plot([], [], lw=2)

def BM_path(time):
    line.set_data(t[:time], BM[:time])
    return (line,)

path_animation = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, BM_path, frames=frames, interval=10, blit=True)
HTML(path_animation.to_html5_video())
